We have a cat. A Norwegian Forest Cat.

He is overwhelmingly black.

Not soft gray black or warm brown black, but deep soot black, the kind of black that absorbs detail until light hits the fur directly. At first glance his coat reads almost as a single dark silhouette, with only subtle tonal variation emerging under stronger light. Those variations are minimal and secondary, appearing only as faint smoke charcoal or muted dark bronze undertones at the very tips of certain guard hairs. The dominant impression is unmistakably black.

His coat is enormous, dense, and heavily layered. The outer fur is long, rugged, and naturally uneven, forming a thick weatherproof shell over an intensely dense undercoat. Around the neck and chest the fur expands outward into a massive mane that resembles dark winter wool or black smoke frozen in motion. The mane does not appear silky or groomed. Instead it has a raw natural texture, with long guard hairs breaking the outline and creating a wild forest-cat silhouette.

The fur around the face is shorter and more compact, almost velvet-like in texture, while the cheeks and neck become dramatically fuller and more turbulent. Across the body the coat remains extremely dark, with depth created more through texture and shadow than through color. Light disappears into the fur rather than reflecting off it, which gives the cat an unusually heavy visual presence. The tail is extraordinarily full and plume-like, thick from base to tip, with dense black feathering that makes it resemble a moving shadow.

His ears are tall, sharply triangular, and highly defined against the softer mass of fur surrounding the head. Fine tufts soften the edges slightly, but the overall shape remains sharp and alert. The ears contribute strongly to his expression, giving him an observant and intensely aware appearance.

The face has a striking balance between softness and severity. Beneath the heavy fur there is a broad forehead, compact muzzle, straight nose bridge, and strong cheek structure partially hidden by the mane. The nose leather blends almost seamlessly into the surrounding fur, making the center of the face feel sculpted from shadow rather than divided into separate features.

His whiskers are long, thin, and silver white, standing out dramatically against the black muzzle. They arc outward in smooth lines and provide one of the only bright elements in the face besides the eyes.

The eyes are pale green with muted icy undertones, and they appear almost luminous against the surrounding darkness. Their shape is slightly almond-like, with narrowed outer corners that create an intensely analytical expression. Because the fur surrounding the eyes is so dark and light absorbing, the eyes become the visual anchor of the entire face, almost appearing to float within the blackness of the coat.

His overall build is large framed and heavy boned, with a broad chest and substantial proportions hidden beneath the massive coat. Despite the density and size of the fur, he does not appear clumsy. He has the physical presence of an animal built for cold weather, climbing, endurance, and balance.

The overall impression is less of a typical domestic cat and more of a living mass of black winter fur, raven feathers, smoke, shadow, and dark forest texture given shape.
